}
```
The run method of thread A reads the first character of the first line of the file. If the character is 'B', it calls the write method to write a new line to the file. If the character is not 'B', it simply prints a message indicating that it took the file. If an exception occurs while reading the file, it is caught and an error message is printed.

```java
public void run() {
    BufferedReader reader;
    while (!Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted()) {
        try {
            reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(new FileInputStream(file)));
            if (reader.readLine().charAt(0) == 'A') {
                System.out.println("B try took file: " + file.getName());
                write();
            } else {
                System.out.println("B took file: " + file.getName());
            }
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("File read B" + e.toString());
        }
        catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("File read B"+e.toString());
        }
    }
}
```
The run method of thread B does the same as thread A, but it checks if the first character of the first line of the file is 'A' instead of 'B'. If it is, it calls the write method to write a new line to the file. If the character is not 'A', it simply prints a message indicating that it took the file. If an exception occurs while reading the file, it is caught and an error message is printed.

These changes ensure that only one thread can write to the file at a time, preventing a race condition.
